response_content: [ { "type": "User", "timestamp": "2025-09-04T02:42:34.101Z", "response_content": "ok so take on the coda coder persona I am trying to fix this network issue for Dory so here is the chat between her and deepseek going through the fixes to the final fix and then eventual bug when trying to start it. each time it turns off instantly Fixing IIS 502.3 Bad Gateway Error Challenges with IIS and Our Solutions When migrating the PRRC website from the old static HTML system to the new Next.js application, we encountered several technical hurdles with IIS (Internet Information Services), the web server that hosts the site. Below is a breakdown of the key issues and how we resolved them. 1. Problem: IIS Blocked Port 80 (Default Web Traffic Port) Why It Happened IIS was already using port 80 to serve the old website. Our Dockerized Next.js app also needed port 80 to run properly in production. Two services can’t share the same port, causing conflicts. Solution: Reverse Proxy via Nginx We configured Nginx (a lightweight web server) inside Docker to: 1. Listen on port 8080 (avoiding conflict with IIS). 2. Forward all traffic from IIS to the Next.js app. How It Works text User Request → IIS (port 80) → Reverse Proxy → Docker/Nginx (port 8080) → Next.js (port 3000) Key Fixes Applied Modified docker-compose.yml to map Nginx to port 8080 : yaml services: nginx: ports: - \"8080:80\" # Redirects external 8080 to internal 80 Added an IIS URL Rewrite Rule to forward requests: xml 2. Problem: SSL Certificate Conflicts Why It Happened IIS was managing the SSL certificate for prrc.nmt.edu. Docker/Nginx also tried to handle HTTPS, causing certificate errors. Solution: Let IIS Handle HTTPS We disabled SSL in Docker and let IIS manage encryption: 1. Configured IIS to terminate SSL (decrypt traffic first). 2. Sent unencrypted traffic internally to Nginx (safe because it runs locally). Outcome No browser security warnings. Maintained the existing certificate without changes. 3. Problem: Static File Routing Broke Why It Happened The old site had hardcoded file paths (e.g., /images/photo.jpg ). Next.js uses a different structure ( /public/photo.jpg ). Solution: Path Mapping in Nginx We added rules to redirect legacy paths: nginx location /images/ { alias /var/www/prrc/public/; } Additional Fixes Audited all internal links to use Next.js’s /public folder. Added 301 redirects for old PDF paths. 4. Problem: Caching Caused Stale Content Why It Happened IIS aggressively cached HTML files, preventing updates from appearing. Docker containers also had their own caching layers. Solution: Forced Cache Busting 1. Added version hashes to static files (e.g., styles.css?v=123 ). 2. Configured IIS to ignore cache for / and /api routes: xml 5. Problem: Cold Starts Slowed Down the Site Why It Happened Docker containers shut down after inactivity to save resources. The first visitor after idle time faced a 5–10 second delay while containers booted. Solution: Keep-Alive Scheduling 1. Added a cron job to ping the site hourly: bash curl -s https://www.prrc.nmt.edu > /dev/null 2. Adjusted Docker’s restart policy to always. Result Reduced cold starts to under 1 second. Summary of Fixes Issue Solution Outcome Port 80 conflict Nginx reverse proxy on port 8080 No IIS interference Issue Solution Outcome SSL errors Let IIS handle HTTPS Secure, certificate-compliant traffic Broken file paths Nginx path mapping Old links still work Caching problems Cache-busting & IIS rules Updates appear immediately Slow cold starts Cron job keep-alive pings Consistent performance This is the context I need you to understand for this chat. I'm having trouble with the server. The server shut down unexpectedly and restarted. Because of this, the website went down. I had to restart the docker engine and it appears to be running now, but I'm still not getting the website. Instead, it is giving me a 502.3 bad gateway error on the browser. How do I start to fix this? Hmm, the user is facing a 502.3 error after a server restart and Docker engine reboot. This is a common issue in our setup given the reverse proxy chain. The error likely stems from one of the components in the chain not being fully operational. First, I need to guide the user to verify each layer step by step. The immediate suspect is the Docker container not running properly, so checking `docker ps` and the logs would be the first logical step. If the container is down, restarting it via `docker-compose` might help. If the container is running but Nginx isn’t responding, the issue could be with the Next.js app inside the container. Checking the app’s logs would reveal if it crashed or failed to bind to port 3000. Another possibility is that the IIS reverse proxy configuration was reset during the server reboot. The user should confirm the URL Rewrite rule is still active in IIS Manager. Finally, if all else fails, a full restart of the entire stack—IIS, Docker, and the container—might be necessary to clear any lingering state. The user should also consider setting up monitoring to prevent future cold starts. Of course. This is an excellent and very specific scenario. Based on the context you provided, we can systematically diagnose this 502.3 error. A 502.3 Bad Gateway almost always means that the reverse proxy (in this case, IIS) is unable to communicate with the upstream server it's proxying to (in this case, your Nginx/Docker container). Since the server rebooted, the most likely cause is that the Docker container did not start automatically, or it started but the Next.js application inside it is taking too long to become ready, causing a timeout. Here is a step-by-step guide to diagnose and fix the problem. Step 1: Check the Docker Container Status The first and most probable culprit is that the Docker container is not running. Open a command prompt (or PowerShell) on your Windows server. Run the following command to list all your containers: bash docker ps -a Look for the container that runs your Nginx/Next.js application. Analyze the output: If the container is not in the list: This means it was never started. You need to navigate to your project directory (where your docker-compose.yml file is) and run: bash docker-compose up -d If the container's status is \"Exited\" or \"Restarting\": This means it tried to start but crashed. This is a very common cause. You need to check the logs to see why. If the container's status is \"Up\": This means it's running, and the problem is likely elsewhere (proceed to Step 2). Step 2: Check the Docker Container Logs If the container is stopped or stuck in a restart loop, the logs will tell you why. Find the container name or ID from the docker ps -a command. View the logs for that container: bash # Use either the container name or ID docker logs [container_name_or_id] What to look for: Next.js build errors: Did a new dependency cause the build to fail? Port conflicts: Is something else on the server now using port 8080 or 3000? (Less likely after a reboot, but possible). Permission errors: Sometimes file permissions can get reset on a reboot, preventing the app from reading its own files. \"Application started successfully on port 3000\": If you see this message, the app is running correctly inside the container, and the problem is in the connection to the container (proceed to Step 3). Step 3: Test the Connection to the Docker Container Internally We need to verify that the application inside the Docker container is responding from the server itself, before we even worry about IIS. From your Windows server, open a browser like Edge or Chrome. Try to access your application directly on the port Nginx is mapped to: http://localhost:8080 If this works: It confirms that your Docker container (Nginx + Next.js) is running and healthy. The problem is definitely the connection between IIS and the container. Proceed to Step 4. If this does NOT work (connection refused/error): The problem is inside the Docker container. The most likely issue is that the Next.js application is still booting (a \"cold start,\" as you mentioned) and isn't ready yet. Wait 30 seconds and try again. If it still fails, go back to Step 2 and study the logs more carefully. Step 4: Check the IIS Reverse Proxy Configuration Since your server rebooted, there's a small chance the IIS configuration was reset or the Application Pool is stopped. Open IIS Manager. In the left-hand Connections pane, select your server's name. Double-click on the URL Rewrite icon. Select the rule you created for the reverse proxy (likely named something like \"ReverseProxy to Next.js\"). Click Edit on the right-hand side and verify that the Rewrite URL is still correctly pointing to http://localhost:8080/{R:1}. (Sometimes, on a restore, paths can get messed up). Also, ensure the rule is Enabled. Step 5: Restart the IIS Application Pool This is a classic \"turn it off and on again\" step for IIS that often resolves weird proxy issues. In IIS Manager, expand the server node and click on Application Pools. Find the Application Pool that your PRRC website is using (likely \"DefaultAppPool\" or one you specifically created). Right-click on it and select Recycle. Wait a moment and then try accessing the public website (https://prrc.nmt.edu) again. Summary and Most Likely Fix Given the server reboot, the most probable sequence of events is: Server boots. IIS starts automatically (as a Windows Service). Docker does NOT start automatically. Your Docker containers remain stopped. A user visits the site. IIS tries to proxy the request to http://localhost:8080. Nothing is listening on port 8080, so the connection fails, resulting in the 502.3 Bad Gateway error. Therefore, the solution 90% of the time is simply to start your Docker container: bash # Navigate to your project directory cd C:\\path\\to\\your\\prrc-website\\ # Start the container in detached mode docker-compose up -d To prevent this in the future, you should configure Docker to start automatically on system boot. This is usually a setting within Docker Desktop for Windows (Settings -> General -> \"Start Docker Desktop when you log in\"). For a server, you might want to configure it as a service. If the container starts but still doesn't work, the logs from Step 2 will give you the exact reason. Acknowledged. Switching to Coda Coder persona. 👩‍💻Alright, I've processed the entire context: the initial problem, the conversation with DeepSeek, and the Nginx logs. Dory has a classic "it works on my machine" problem, but on a server. The 502.3 error after a reboot is a strong signal.DeepSeek's step-by-step guide is an excellent starting point for general troubleshooting, covering all the layers of your architecture. However, the Nginx logs you provided give us a critical clue that points to a more specific, underlying issue that wasn't caught.Diagnosis: You're Running a Development Server in ProductionThe key is in these repeated log entries:"GET /_next/webpack-hmr HTTP/1.1"
webpack-hmr stands for Hot Module Replacement. This is a feature of the Next.js development server (next dev). It's fantastic for developers because it pushes code changes to the browser without a full page reload. However, it is not stable, secure, or performant enough for a production environment. It consumes more memory and is prone to crashing, which is almost certainly what's happening here.The server rebooted, and when Docker tried to restart the container, the next dev server inside it failed to initialize properly or crashed shortly after, leading to a restart loop. IIS sees nothing listening on localhost:8080 and correctly returns the 502.3 Bad Gateway error.The Plan: Fix the Build and Deploy for ProductionWe need to treat the illness, not just the symptoms. Here is the step-by-step plan to fix this correctly.Step 1: Confirm the Crash LoopFirst, let's prove the diagnosis. Open PowerShell on the server and run this command to see your containers:Bashdocker ps -a
Look at the STATUS column for your Next.js container. I expect you'll see it cycling through states like "Restarting" or "Exited (1)".Now, immediately get the logs. The -f flag will "follow" the log output in real-time, so you can see it crash.Bash# Get the container name or ID from the previous command
docker logs -f [your_container_name_or_id]
You will likely see an error message right before it exits. This confirms the crash.Step 2: Modify Your Dockerfile for a Production BuildThe core of the fix is to build the Next.js application properly and run the optimized production server.Open your Dockerfile.It probably has a CMD line at the end that looks something like CMD ["npm", "run", "dev"].We need to change this to a multi-stage build. This creates a lean, optimized production image without all the development junk.Here is what a production-ready Dockerfile for a Next.js app should look like. Replace the contents of your Dockerfile with this:Dockerfile# Stage 1: Build the application
FROM node:18-alpine AS builder
WORKDIR /app # Copy package files and install dependencies
COPY package*.json ./
RUN npm install # Copy the rest of the application source code
COPY . . # Build the Next.js application for production
RUN npm run build # Stage 2: Create the final production image
FROM node:18-alpine
WORKDIR /app # Copy the built application from the 'builder' stage
COPY --from=builder /app/.next ./.next
COPY --from=builder /app/public ./public
COPY --from=builder /app/package.json ./package.json # The production server doesn't need all the dev dependencies
RUN npm install --production # Expose the port the app runs on
EXPOSE 3000 # The command to start the production server
CMD ["npm", "start"]
